        - HR as a final end.

            HR. The conjunction of ends H and R.
            H. Humanity extant through all reasonable ends.
                - For any reasonable end E that would obtain at time tE,
                  humanity continues to exist through tE.
                - A reasonable end is one which both a) is realistic,
                  and b) we have reason to value, whether in its own right,
                  or as a condition of a further end which itself is reasonable.
                    : see `^^evaluation of ends$`
            R. Full exercise of our capacity for reason.
                - Here â€˜fullâ€™ means the maximum that realistically we could sustain at a given time.

        - If ever we judge from the high vantage of R that no component end remains to be achieved,
          then HR itself will have been achieved.
            - Then we might reasonably allow or seek extinction, but not before then.
            / And if instead we come to judge that our rational nature (or capacity for reason)
              is valuable in its own right, as did Kant, then we will seek to expand it
              and prolong its exercise indefinitely, and so defy extinction.
